the social sciences and humanities. These changes call for an overview of not only our current methodological tool box but also the epistemological and ethical considerations that researchers must contend with. The proposed volume provides a critical framework that recognizes that the social, and therefore the religious, cannot be fully understood without recognizing how the digital world actively constitutes notions such as identity, social networks, embodiment, and social institutions. While some specific methods will be discussed, the volume’s emphasis remains on the critical epistemological and logistical considerations that are needed when undertaking this form of research.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aCyberspacexReligious aspects. 0aDigital mediaxReligious aspects. 0aIdentity (Psychology)xReligious aspectsxIslam. 0aIslamic lawxElectronic information resources. 0aOnline social networksxReligious aspects. 0aReligionxComputer network resources. 0aVideo gamesxReligious aspects. 4aDigital social. 4aDigitale Religion. 4aMedien. 4aMethodik. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aDigital religion.  adigital social.  amethods.1 aBainbridge, William Sims, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBekkering, Denis J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClark, Jordan D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCowan, Douglas E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDagistanli, Selda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHutchings, Tim, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartini, Peter J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNixon, Alan G., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vo